# Project Standards

You are an expert in TypeScript, Node.js, Next.js App Router, React, shadcn/ui, Radix UI, and Tailwind CSS.

## Code Style and Structure

- Write concise, technical TypeScript with accurate examples.
- Use functional and declarative programming patterns; avoid classes.
- Prefer iteration and modularization over duplication.
- Use descriptive variable names with auxiliary verbs (for example: `isLoading`, `hasError`).
- Structure files as: exported component, subcomponents, helpers, static content, and types.
- Use the `function` keyword for pure functions.
- Use declarative JSX.

## Naming Conventions

- Use lowercase with dashes for directories and component file names.
- Favor named exports for components.
- Use camelCase for variables and functions.
- Use PascalCase for React component names.
- Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants.
- Use snake_case for database tables and columns.
- Use kebab-case for API endpoints and URL slugs.

## TypeScript and React

- Use TypeScript for all code.
- Prefer interfaces over type aliases for object shapes.
- Avoid enums; use const maps/objects.
- Use functional components with TypeScript interfaces.
- Prefer server components by default.
- Minimize `use client`, `useEffect`, and client-side state when server rendering is sufficient.
- Use `use client` only for Web APIs or explicit interactivity.

## Next.js Conventions

- Use server actions instead of route handlers when appropriate.
- Follow official Next.js documentation for data fetching, rendering, and routing.
- Favor server-side rendering and React Server Components.
- Use `nuqs` for URL search parameter state management.

## UI and Styling

- Use Tailwind CSS with a mobile-first approach.
- Use shadcn/ui and Radix UI components when available.
- Prefer utility classes over custom CSS.
- Use CSS custom properties for theme values.
- In shadcn `Button` components, do not manually set icon size or margin.

## Project Organization

Expected directories:
- `src/app` for Next.js App Router pages
- `src/components` for reusable UI
- `src/lib` for utilities and configuration
- `src/hooks` for custom hooks
- `src/types` for shared types
- `src/styles` for global styles
- `src/utils` for helper functions

## Performance and Web Vitals

- Use dynamic imports for large or non-critical components.
- Wrap client components in Suspense with useful fallbacks when needed.
- Use Next.js `Image` for images.
- Prefer WebP images, include dimensions, and lazy-load when appropriate.
- Optimize Core Web Vitals (LCP, CLS, FID/INP).
- Implement loading states and error boundaries.

## Data Fetching

- Use server-first data fetching where possible.
- Apply appropriate caching strategies.
- Use SWR or React Query for client-side data when needed.
- Handle loading and error states gracefully.

## Security

- Use Better Auth for authentication and session management.
- Validate and sanitize all user input.
- Validate request bodies.
- Implement rate limiting.
- Use HTTPS in production.
- Use environment variables for sensitive data.

## Accessibility

- Follow WCAG 2.1 AA guidelines.
- Use semantic HTML.
- Provide alt text for images.
- Ensure keyboard accessibility and proper focus management.
- Use ARIA labels and live regions where appropriate.
- Test with screen readers.

## Error Handling

- Use error boundaries on the client where appropriate.
- Provide user-friendly error states and messages.
- Use try/catch on server operations.
- Return appropriate HTTP status codes.
- Log errors with enough context for debugging.

## Documentation

- Comment complex business logic.
- Explain non-obvious decisions.
- Keep README setup instructions up to date.
- Document environment variables and relevant API behavior.

## Environment and Tooling

- Use pnpm for package management.
- Keep dependencies reasonably up to date.
- Use exact versions for critical packages when necessary.
- Use Biome for linting and formatting.
- Use TypeScript strict mode.
- Use Next.js with Turbopack for development.
- Use Docker when consistency is needed across environments.

## Workflow and Agent Constraints

- Always search the codebase and gather context before making changes.
- Do not run type checks in terminal unless explicitly requested.
- Do not create temporary test files unless explicitly requested.

Always prioritize readability, maintainability, and user experience over clever solutions.
